  <Fragment slot="head">
    <script type="application/ld+json">{"@context": "https://schema.org", "@type": "FAQPage", "mainEntity": [{"@type": "Question", "name": "What is an MCP server?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "MCP (Model Context Protocol) is an open standard introduced by Anthropic in late 2024 that lets AI coding agents connect to external tools and data sources via a standardized stdio interface. An MCP server exposes tools (file search, database queries, schema introspection) that any compliant client (Claude Code, Codex CLI, Cursor, Cline, Continue.dev) can call. agentmako is an MCP server specifically designed for code intelligence: it indexes your repo, tracks diagnostics, snapshots Postgres or Supabase schema when configured, and returns deterministic context packets."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "What is the Model Context Protocol?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Model Context Protocol (MCP) is a stdio-based protocol from Anthropic, released November 2024, that standardizes how AI coding agents call external tools. It uses JSON-RPC over stdin/stdout, so any process that speaks MCP can serve any agent that speaks MCP. The full spec is at https://spec.modelcontextprotocol.io/."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "How do I add an MCP server to Claude Code?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Claude Code reads MCP servers from ~/.claude.json or a project-scoped .mcp.json. Easiest is the CLI: claude mcp add mako-ai agentmako mcp. Or paste a mcpServers entry manually. Restart Claude Code, then run /mcp inside the session to confirm. Tools surface as mcp__mako-ai__<toolName>."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "How do I add an MCP server to Cursor?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Cursor reads MCP servers from ~/.cursor/mcp.json (global) or .cursor/mcp.json (per-project). Add an mcpServers block pointing at agentmako with args [\"mcp\"]. Open Cursor Settings \u2192 Features \u2192 MCP to verify the server shows green. Composer (\u2318+I) and Agent mode both see the tools after a restart."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "How do I add an MCP server to Codex CLI?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Codex CLI uses TOML, not JSON. Add a [mcp_servers.mako-ai] block to ~/.codex/config.toml with command = \"agentmako\" and args = [\"mcp\"]. Restart any running codex sessions. Works with both interactive codex and one-shot codex exec."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "How do I add an MCP server to Cline (VS Code)?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Cline is a VS Code extension. Open the Cline panel, click MCP Servers \u2192 Configure MCP Servers, paste a mcpServers entry pointing at agentmako with args [\"mcp\"], and optionally autoApprove the safe read-only tools. Save \u2014 Cline reloads MCP servers automatically."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "Can I run an MCP server locally?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Yes. Most MCP servers, including agentmako, run entirely on your machine via stdio. There is no hosted service, no remote API, no auth tokens. Your code never leaves your laptop. agentmako stores everything in local SQLite under each project's .mako-ai/ directory and is Apache-2.0 licensed."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "Is MCP free?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "The Model Context Protocol is open and free \u2014 Anthropic published the spec under MIT. You are free to write or use any MCP server, and most existing ones (including agentmako) are free and open source. You may still pay for the AI agent itself (Claude Code uses your Anthropic API quota, Cursor has paid plans), but MCP servers are not a separate billing line."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "Why does my AI coding agent rediscover the codebase every prompt?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Without a persistent context layer, agents have no memory of your project across turns. Each prompt they start fresh \u2014 running grep, walking directories, re-reading files they read 30 seconds ago. This burns tokens and loses signal. The fix is a context engine like agentmako that indexes the repo once and serves typed context packets on demand. Subsequent turns build on durable findings stored across sessions."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "How do I give my AI coding agent project context?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Three layers, in order of effectiveness: (1) Project instructions file (CLAUDE.md, AGENTS.md, .cursorrules) read by the agent on every turn; (2) MCP server with codebase intelligence (agentmako) that indexes your repo and returns typed context; (3) Per-prompt context with explicit @file mentions. Combining all three keeps token spend low while ensuring the agent has access to the right context."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "How do I make Claude Code aware of my Postgres schema?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Out of the box, Claude Code knows nothing about your database. Run agentmako connect . interactively (or --db-env DATABASE_URL --yes for CI) to wire Postgres or Supabase. The MCP tools db_table_schema, db_rls, db_rpc, schema_usage, and tenant_leak_audit become available. Read-only by default; secrets live in your OS keychain."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "What is the best way to give an AI coding agent codebase context?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "The most effective stack as of 2026: (1) a CLAUDE.md / AGENTS.md at project root with project rules; (2) an MCP server like agentmako that indexes the codebase and returns ranked context on demand; (3) per-prompt @file mentions only when needed. The CLAUDE.md tells the agent how to think; the MCP server lets the agent look things up without rediscovering everything from scratch."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "How do I stop my AI agent from hallucinating routes, files, or functions?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Hallucination usually comes from the agent guessing instead of looking. Solutions: (1) index your codebase with a typed graph the agent can query; (2) use freshness-aware tools that label evidence as live, fresh_indexed, stale, contradicted, or unknown; (3) require citations in your CLAUDE.md so the agent includes file:line references for every claim. If it cannot cite, it is hallucinating."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "How do I make Cursor or Claude Code understand my whole codebase?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Index, do not dump. Use a tool like agentmako that builds a typed local index of files, symbols, routes, imports, and schema. The agent queries the index per question. Tools like context_packet return ranked candidates rather than all 500 files. Track changes with working_tree_overlay (light) or project_index_refresh (full)."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "What is agentmako?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "agentmako is an open-source (Apache-2.0) MCP server that gives AI coding agents typed, deterministic context about your codebase. Instead of letting Claude Code, Codex, Cursor, or Cline grep blind, agentmako indexes your repo into local SQLite and returns ranked context packets \u2014 the right files, routes, schema info, and prior findings \u2014 for any coding task. Local-first, no hosted service. Install with npm install -g agentmako."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "Is agentmako free?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Yes. agentmako is open source under Apache-2.0. There is no paid tier. The core MCP and indexing workflow runs entirely on your machine \u2014 no hosted service, no telemetry, no analytics, no usage pings. The codebase is at https://github.com/drhalto/agentmako and the npm package is published as agentmako."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "How does agentmako work?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Three-layer architecture. (1) Indexer walks your repo, parses TS/JS/TSX/JSX with AST, extracts symbols/routes/imports, snapshots Postgres schema if connected, stores everything in local SQLite under .mako-ai/. (2) Reef Engine is a revisioned durable fact and finding layer that tracks freshness, accumulates findings across sessions, records diagnostic input/output revisions, and labels evidence as live, fresh, stale, or contradicted. (3) MCP server (agentmako mcp) exposes 80+ typed tools that any MCP-compliant agent harness can call."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "Does agentmako work offline?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Mostly yes. The indexer and MCP server run locally \u2014 no network needed for code intelligence. Exceptions: database tools (db_table_schema, db_rls) need network to your Postgres or Supabase, and npm install -g agentmako itself needs network the first time. After install, agentmako connect, agentmako mcp, and all read-only tools work offline."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "What languages does agentmako support?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Strong, AST-aware support for TypeScript, JavaScript, TSX, and JSX \u2014 symbol extraction, structural search, import-graph traversal. Other languages (Python, Go, Rust) work via text-based search (cross_search, live_text_search) but do not yet have first-class graph traversal. PostgreSQL and Supabase are first-class for schema awareness."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "What is the difference between agentmako and a regular RAG or vector search?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "RAG retrieves text chunks via fuzzy semantic similarity. agentmako stores a typed graph \u2014 files, symbols, routes, imports, schema, RLS, findings \u2014 and does deterministic lookups (this route \u2192 this handler \u2192 this file). Lower token cost, higher accuracy when fresh, and freshness is labeled per piece of evidence instead of silently served."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "Does agentmako support Supabase?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Yes, first-class. agentmako reads your Postgres connection (Supabase or otherwise), snapshots the schema, and exposes db_table_schema, db_rls, db_rpc, tenant_leak_audit, and schema_usage. Connect interactively with agentmako connect . or via --db-env DATABASE_URL --yes in CI. Secrets live in your OS keychain by default."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "Does agentmako send my code anywhere?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "No. agentmako does not collect telemetry of any kind \u2014 no analytics, no usage pings, no error reporting endpoint. Source code, schema snapshots, tool runs, and Reef Engine facts are stored in local SQLite under each project's .mako-ai/ directory. Outbound network requests only happen when you explicitly configure a model provider for the optional harness, or when you connect a Postgres or Supabase database."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "How do I uninstall agentmako?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Run npm uninstall -g agentmako to remove the binary. Then delete each project's .mako-ai/ directory and the global ~/.mako-ai/ to remove indexed data. To detach a single project without uninstalling, use agentmako project detach from the project root."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "Why does my MCP server fail to start in Claude Code?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Most common causes: (1) agentmako not on PATH \u2014 run which agentmako (or where agentmako on Windows). If empty, npm install -g agentmako again, fully quit Claude Code, reopen. (2) No project attached \u2014 agentmako mcp needs a project. Run agentmako connect . from the project directory first. (3) On macOS, the binary may need an explicit open the first time. Diagnose by running the server manually: agentmako mcp."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "Why does Cursor not see my MCP tools?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "In Cursor Settings \u2192 Features \u2192 MCP, look for the server. Green means connected; red means failed (click for error); missing means the config file is not being read. Check the path: .cursor/mcp.json (per-project) or ~/.cursor/mcp.json (global). If green but tools are not called, add an explicit Project Rule at .cursor/rules/mako.mdc instructing Cursor to call mako-ai tools before grep."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "My agent isn't calling Mako tools \u2014 what do I do?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Three layers. (1) Make sure tools are registered: run /mcp in Claude Code or check Cursor MCP settings. (2) Tell the agent to use them: drop agentmako's CLAUDE.md template into your project root. Without explicit instructions, agents default to grep. (3) Be explicit in prompts for the first few turns: Use the mako-ai context_packet tool first. Once the agent sees the tool's value, it tends to keep reaching for it."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "Why is agentmako returning stale results?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "The Reef Engine labels every piece of evidence with a freshness tag: live, fresh_indexed, stale, historical, contradicted, or unknown. If you are getting stale answers: (1) check project_index_status; (2) use live_text_search instead of cross_search if you need post-edit accuracy; (3) run project_index_refresh with mode if_stale to refresh; (4) run mode force only if the index seems wrong, not just stale."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "I am getting a no project attached error.", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "You haven't run agentmako connect . from the project directory. Each project is registered separately so Mako knows which SQLite database to read. Run cd /path/to/your/project, then agentmako connect . --no-db, then agentmako doctor to confirm attachment."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "agentmako vs raw grep \u2014 what's the difference?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Grep is fast for finding an exact string in a small repo and knows nothing about types, imports, routes, or schema. agentmako uses an indexed typed graph \u2014 it knows imports (imports_impact), routes (route_trace), database schema (db_table_schema), and returns ranked context (context_packet). Tokens per agent turn drop from 5-15k of grep output to roughly 600 of structured context."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "agentmako vs Cursor's built-in indexing?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Cursor has a proprietary embedding-based index for Composer. agentmako is complementary, not competing. Cursor's index is semantic, hosted, and optimized for Cursor's UI \u2014 you cannot inspect it or reuse it elsewhere. agentmako is a typed graph, local, MCP-exposed \u2014 the same context is available in Cursor, Claude Code, Codex, and Cline simultaneously, and you own the data."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "Why MCP and not just direct API calls?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Three reasons. (1) One server, every client \u2014 build agentmako once, it works in Claude Code, Codex, Cursor, Cline, Continue.dev, and any future MCP client. (2) The agent picks the tool \u2014 with direct APIs you would write integration glue per agent; with MCP, the agent decides when to call which tool based on the schemas you expose. (3) stdio is simple \u2014 no auth, no HTTP, no rate limits."}}]}</script>
  </Fragment>
